2. Technical Deep-Dive Topics
A. Kotlin & Coroutines
	•	Structured concurrency: CoroutineScope, Job vs SupervisorJob
	•	Dispatchers.Main/IO/Default — when to use each
	•	Flow vs StateFlow vs SharedFlow vs LiveData — trade-offs
	•	Exception handling: try/catch inside coroutines vs CoroutineExceptionHandler
	•	Cancellation cooperation (isActive, ensureActive())
	•	Sealed classes, data classes, extension functions, inline/reified functions
Sample Q: "Walk me through how you'd handle a coroutine that needs to survive configuration changes but should be cancelled when the ViewModel is cleared." Strong answer angle: Use viewModelScope, explain it's tied to ViewModel.onCleared(), contrast with lifecycleScope which dies on rotation without special handling, mention repeatOnLifecycle for UI-safe collection of Flows.
B. Jetpack Compose
	•	Recomposition mechanics: what triggers it, @Stable / @Immutable, skipping
	•	remember, derivedStateOf, LaunchedEffect, SideEffect
	•	State hoisting & unidirectional data flow (UDF)
	•	Performance pitfalls: lambda allocation in loops, unstable list keys, heavy composables without key()
	•	Compose interop with existing XML views (ComposeView, AndroidView)
Sample Q: "A screen with a list of 500 transactions is janky when scrolling. How do you debug and fix it in Compose?" Strong answer angle: Use LazyColumn with stable key = { it.id }, check for unnecessary recompositions with Layout Inspector, memoize expensive calculations with remember/derivedStateOf, avoid creating new lambdas/objects per item, consider Modifier reuse, and profile with Compose Compiler metrics/reports.
C. Architecture
	•	MVVM / MVI / Clean Architecture layering (data / domain / presentation)
	•	DI with Hilt/Dagger — component scoping, @Singleton vs @ActivityScoped
	•	Modularization: feature modules, core/common modules, build time optimization, dependency graph management
	•	Repository pattern, single source of truth, offline-first design
Sample Q: "How would you structure a large banking app into modules?" Strong answer angle: Core modules (network, database, design-system, common-ui) + feature modules (accounts, transfers, cards) that depend only on core, never on each other directly — communicate via a navigation/routing abstraction or shared domain module. Discuss build time wins and team ownership boundaries.
